Timed texts.

A timed text is an invisible, silent zone that speaks a written message to the player at a set interval for as long as they stand inside it. There is no sound clip and nothing to hear spatially — the message goes straight to the screen reader, the same way the game announces anything else. Timed texts are the way to attach repeating spoken narration to a place: an ambient line that sets a scene, a warning that nags while the player lingers somewhere dangerous, or a hint that keeps reminding them what to do until they move on.

How timed text works.

A timed text fills a single tile or a rectangular area and watches the player's position. While the player stands anywhere inside it, the message is spoken once every interval, over and over, until they step out. Leaving the area stops the repetition, and stepping back in starts it again. A timed text has no footprint the player can otherwise sense — it makes no sound, blocks nothing, and is felt only through the spoken message. On 3d maps the area also spans between its minimum and maximum height.

Timed text fields.

The timed text form takes the following:

Build mode. Single for one exact tile, or ranged for a rectangular area. Single is the default.

Coordinates. For a single timed text, an x and a y (and a z on 3d maps) — the one tile it sits on. For a ranged timed text, a minimum and maximum x and a minimum and maximum y (and a minimum and maximum z on 3d maps), marking the rectangle it fills.

Speed. The number of milliseconds between each repetition of the message, so a smaller number speaks it more often.

Text. The message that gets spoken. It can contain spaces and keeps the exact text you type.

Authoring timed texts by hand.

If you edit main.sif directly, a timed text is written under the name timed_text. A single one is timed_text x y speed "text", and on 3d maps a z follows the y: timed_text x y z speed "text". A ranged one is timed_text minx maxx miny maxy speed "text", and on 3d maps a minimum and maximum z follow the y pair: timed_text minx maxx miny maxy minz maxz speed "text". Both forms share the one timed_text name — the line is read as ranged when more coordinates sit before the quoted text. The speed is a number of milliseconds, and the message is wrapped in double quotes so it can hold spaces.
